Urban Redcedar Analyses - Welcome

Joey Hulbert

2023-04-16

Welcome Data Analyses Discussion

Intro

The RedHot analyses were completed to study relationships between the health of western redcedar and urban environmental factors.

  • We were interested in the factors that affect urban tree health such as:
    • Urban Heat
    • Impermeable Surface
    • Pollution
    • Climate Variables
    • Wealth
    • Tree Size
    • Tree Species

Data

  • Analyses were completed with the following Data
    • Redcedar health data were collected by community scientists in the Western Redcedar Dieback Map project on iNaturalist.
    • Urban heat data were commissioned by three cities in the northwest using methods described in Voelkel and Shandas (2017).
    • Home Owners Loan Corporation Maps were downloaded from the Mapping Inequality Project at the following links
      • Tacoma
      • Portland
      • Seattle
    • Environmental Health Disparity Data were downloaded from the Washington Tracking Network

Data for the below metrics are included in the data, but not all have been investigated in the analyses yet.

  • Available data presently
    • Diesel exhaust
    • Ozone
    • Urban Heat
    • Wealth - poverty
    • Tree size
    • Proximity to heavy traffic roadways

Approaches

The relationship between redcedar and urban metrics were investigated with generalized mixed effect models. More information about the analyses is available

Extra Questions

  • Possible additional questions to explore
    • Which pollution data are important for determining tree health?
    • Are Temperatures higher for trees in urban areas of King County?
    • Are income and tree size important effects for the vulnerability of redcedar to urban heat?
